(
<figureCitation box="[158,295,722,747]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="2.[151,263,1323,1346]" captionTargetBox="[175,1395,312,1273]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[150,1436,301,1302]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Dilobopterus nelsoni sp. nov. 1, head, pronotum, and mesonotum, dorsal view (male paratype). 2, forewing. 3 – 8, male genitalia. 3, pygofer, lateral view. 4, valve and subgenital plate, ventral view. 5, connective and style, dorsal view. 6, ejaculatory reservoir, aedeagus, and basal segment of anal tube, lateral view. 7, paraphyses, laterodorsal view. 8, paraphyses, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1 = 1 mm, 2 = 2 mm, 3 – 8 = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/815999/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="128">Figures 1–8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[307,336,722,747]" captionStart="FIGURES 26 – 29" captionStartId="6.[151,263,1653,1676]" captionTargetBox="[184,1378,948,1599]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,916,1632]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 26 – 29. Body in dorsal view (antennae and legs not depicted). 26, Dilobopterus nelsoni sp. nov., male holotype (total length 6.7 mm). 27, D. sakakibara sp. nov., male holotype (t. l. 6.9 mm). 28, D. segmentalis (Signoret, 1853), male (t. l. 9.0 mm). 29, D. trinotatus (Signoret, 1853), female (t. l. 9.0 mm). The last three species belong to the trinotatus group (see text for details)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/816005/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="128">26</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
