<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1477,2006]" pageId="2" pageNumber="129">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1729,1754]" pageId="2" pageNumber="129">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species is described in honor of our colleague and friend Prof. Dr. Nelson Ferreira Junior (Departamento de Zoologia, Instituto de Biologia, Universidade Federal do 
<collectingRegion box="[1019,1187,1765,1790]" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="2" pageNumber="129">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
) in recognition of his contribution to the study of Brazilian aquatic beetles. He was the collector of the 
<typeStatus box="[1060,1108,1802,1826]" pageId="2" pageNumber="129">type</typeStatus>
series.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1477,2006]" pageId="2" pageNumber="129">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,406,1837,1862]" pageId="2" pageNumber="129">Taxonomic notes.</emphasis>
Among the known 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1850" box="[629,777,1837,1861]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Dilobopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[629,777,1837,1861]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="129">Dilobopterus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Quintas &amp; Felix &amp; Lima &amp; Mejdalani, 2017" authorityName="Quintas &amp; Felix &amp; Lima &amp; Mejdalani" authorityYear="2017" box="[879,995,1837,1861]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Dilobopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nelsoni" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[879,995,1837,1861]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="129">D. nelsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1002,1092,1837,1862]" pageId="2" pageNumber="129" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1002,1092,1837,1862]" pageId="2" pageNumber="129">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Fabricius, 1803" authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1803" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Dilobopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="demissus">
<emphasis box="[1300,1436,1837,1861]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="129">D. demissus</emphasis>
(Fabricius, 1803)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Germar, 1821" authorityName="Germar" authorityYear="1821" box="[363,659,1873,1898]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Dilobopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dispar">
<emphasis box="[363,470,1873,1897]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="129">D. dispar</emphasis>
(Germar, 1821)
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Young, 1977" authorityName="Young, 1977" authorityYear="1977" box="[723,1036,1873,1898]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Dilobopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="disparulus">
<emphasis box="[723,878,1873,1897]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="129">D. disparulus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Young" box="[887,1036,1874,1898]" pageId="2" pageNumber="129" refString="Young, D. A. (1977) Taxonomic study of the Cicadellinae (Homoptera: Cicadellidae). Part 2. New World Cicadellini and the genus Cicadella. Bulletin of the North Carolina Agricultural Experiment Station, 239, 1 - 1135." type="journal article" year="1977">Young, 1977</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. In these three species, the ground color of the anterior dorsum is dark brown or black with brown or yellow marks (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Wilson" box="[1126,1338,1909,1934]" pageId="2" pageNumber="129" refString="Wilson, M. R., Turner, J. A. &amp; McKamey, S. H. (2009) Sharpshooter leafhoppers of the world (Hemiptera: Cicadellidae subfamily Cicadellinae). National Museum Wales. Available from: http: // naturalhistory. museumwales. ac. uk / sharpshooters / home. php (accessed 26 July 2016)" type="journal article" year="2009">
Wilson 
<emphasis box="[1214,1272,1909,1933]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="129">et al.</emphasis>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
) and the rami of the paraphyses are asymmetrical. 
<taxonomicName authority="Quintas &amp; Felix &amp; Lima &amp; Mejdalani, 2017" authorityName="Quintas &amp; Felix &amp; Lima &amp; Mejdalani" authorityYear="2017" box="[643,882,1945,1969]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Dilobopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nelsoni" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[643,882,1945,1969]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="129">Dilobopterus nelsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[893,987,1945,1970]" pageId="2" pageNumber="129" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[893,987,1945,1970]" pageId="2" pageNumber="129">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be distinguished from these three species, as well as from the remaining ones of the genus, by the following combination of features: (1) crown (
<figureCitation box="[1380,1436,1981,2006]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="2.[151,263,1323,1346]" captionTargetBox="[175,1395,312,1273]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[150,1436,301,1302]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Dilobopterus nelsoni sp. nov. 1, head, pronotum, and mesonotum, dorsal view (male paratype). 2, forewing. 3 – 8, male genitalia. 3, pygofer, lateral view. 4, valve and subgenital plate, ventral view. 5, connective and style, dorsal view. 6, ejaculatory reservoir, aedeagus, and basal segment of anal tube, lateral view. 7, paraphyses, laterodorsal view. 8, paraphyses, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1 = 1 mm, 2 = 2 mm, 3 – 8 = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/815999/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="129">Figs.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,357]" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">
1, 
<figureCitation box="[179,208,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 26 – 29" captionStartId="6.[151,263,1653,1676]" captionTargetBox="[184,1378,948,1599]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,916,1632]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 26 – 29. Body in dorsal view (antennae and legs not depicted). 26, Dilobopterus nelsoni sp. nov., male holotype (total length 6.7 mm). 27, D. sakakibara sp. nov., male holotype (t. l. 6.9 mm). 28, D. segmentalis (Signoret, 1853), male (t. l. 9.0 mm). 29, D. trinotatus (Signoret, 1853), female (t. l. 9.0 mm). The last three species belong to the trinotatus group (see text for details)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/816005/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">26</figureCitation>
) with eight small yellow spots, being three pairs around the ocelli and one pair on the central portion close to the posterior margin (an additional pair can be present on the apical portion); (2) stalk of the paraphyses (
<figureCitation box="[1359,1427,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="2.[151,263,1323,1346]" captionTargetBox="[175,1395,312,1273]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[150,1436,301,1302]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Dilobopterus nelsoni sp. nov. 1, head, pronotum, and mesonotum, dorsal view (male paratype). 2, forewing. 3 – 8, male genitalia. 3, pygofer, lateral view. 4, valve and subgenital plate, ventral view. 5, connective and style, dorsal view. 6, ejaculatory reservoir, aedeagus, and basal segment of anal tube, lateral view. 7, paraphyses, laterodorsal view. 8, paraphyses, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1 = 1 mm, 2 = 2 mm, 3 – 8 = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/815999/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) elongate, expanded apically and with a pair of processes directed anteriorly; (3) rami of the paraphyses (
<figureCitation box="[1321,1428,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="2.[151,263,1323,1346]" captionTargetBox="[175,1395,312,1273]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[150,1436,301,1302]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Dilobopterus nelsoni sp. nov. 1, head, pronotum, and mesonotum, dorsal view (male paratype). 2, forewing. 3 – 8, male genitalia. 3, pygofer, lateral view. 4, valve and subgenital plate, ventral view. 5, connective and style, dorsal view. 6, ejaculatory reservoir, aedeagus, and basal segment of anal tube, lateral view. 7, paraphyses, laterodorsal view. 8, paraphyses, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1 = 1 mm, 2 = 2 mm, 3 – 8 = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/815999/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">Figs. 7–8</figureCitation>
) strongly asymmetrical and armed with spines (left ramus with a larger spine basally and a smaller one medially; right ramus bifurcated basally into ventral and dorsal arms, both armed with an inner spine); and (4) dorsal lobe of the aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[310,377,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="2.[151,263,1323,1346]" captionTargetBox="[175,1395,312,1273]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[150,1436,301,1302]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Dilobopterus nelsoni sp. nov. 1, head, pronotum, and mesonotum, dorsal view (male paratype). 2, forewing. 3 – 8, male genitalia. 3, pygofer, lateral view. 4, valve and subgenital plate, ventral view. 5, connective and style, dorsal view. 6, ejaculatory reservoir, aedeagus, and basal segment of anal tube, lateral view. 7, paraphyses, laterodorsal view. 8, paraphyses, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1 = 1 mm, 2 = 2 mm, 3 – 8 = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/815999/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="130">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) large, without emarginations or processes.
</paragraph>
